

If you discover a security vulnerability in {{ project_name }},
please report it responsibly.

**Do NOT open a public GitHub issue for security vulnerabilities.**

Instead, please email the maintainers at **{{ author_email }}**.


- Description of the vulnerability.
- Steps to reproduce.
- Potential impact assessment.
- Suggested fix, if any.


| Action | Timeframe |
|--------|-----------|
| Acknowledgement | Within 48 hours |
| Initial assessment | Within 5 business days |
| Patch release | Within 30 days of confirmation |


The following are in scope for security reports:

- {{ project_name }} backend API.
- Authentication and authorization flows.
- Data storage and encryption.
- Container images published by this project.
- CI/CD pipeline configuration.

Out of scope:

- Third-party dependencies (report upstream instead).
- Denial-of-service attacks against development environments.


| Version | Supported |
|---------|-----------|
| Latest  | Yes       |


- Dependencies updated regularly via Renovate.
- Security scanning in CI pipeline (CodeQL, pip-audit).
- Pre-commit hooks to prevent credential leaks.
- SAST analysis on pull requests.
- Non-root container images with read-only filesystems.
- Security headers middleware (CSP, HSTS, X-Frame-Options).
- Rate limiting on API endpoints.
{% if use_sftp %}

## SSH / SFTP Hardening

- Ed25519 keys by default; RSA 4096-bit as fallback.
- Password authentication disabled (`PasswordAuthentication no`).
- Root login disabled (`PermitRootLogin no`).
- Maximum three authentication attempts (`MaxAuthTries 3`).
- TCP / agent / X11 forwarding disabled unless explicitly needed.
- SFTP users chroot-jailed to their upload directory.
- Drop-in sshd configuration (`sshd_config.d/`) with syntax validation before reload.
- Private keys excluded from version control via `.gitignore`.
- See [SSH/SFTP documentation](docs/SSH_SFTP.md) for full details.
